This paper focuses on multi-turn conversation understanding and retrieval-based response matching, which are core topics in the field of natural language processing and dialogue systems. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a deep learning model for utterance aggregation, which involves neural network architecture design and optimization, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a likely sub-category as well. The model also involves attention mechanisms and matching scores, which are common techniques in machine learning and deep learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category. The paper also evaluates the proposed model on three multi-turn conversation benchmarks, which involves experimental design and analysis, making cs.IR (Information Retrieval) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper focuses on building intelligent dialogue systems, which involves human-computer interaction and user modeling, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a possible sub-category.
